Anonymous Mon 16 Oct 2023 06:24:34 No.60372429 Report

>>60365343
Not those anons but I feel like answering some of those questions.

>Do you all just write on a whim?
My writing is on a 'whenever I feel like it' sort of schedule. I've tried creating a set schedule for writing and while it does allow me to shit out words at a specific time of day I find that what I write tends to feel very robotic and stiff, lacking in fluidity or creativity. I think this just boils down to the fact that writing is a recreational activity for me so while I can force myself to do it my results are best when I feel the inspiration coming and the words flow naturally. That isn't to say that lack of progress on a major work for a period of time can't motivate me to finish it, because it totally does, but trying to shit out words for the sake of shitting out words never ends well.

>Outlines? Notes?
Big yes to both of those. The common wisdom is that there are two kinds of writers, planners and pantsers. Planners tend to outline and plan their scenes/arcs/stories out in advance while pantsers do the opposite and simply let the words flow, figuring things out as they go along. In reality most writers are somewhere in between. However, and I'm not trying to call anyone out here, but it tends to be very easy to tell which writers figure things out as they go versus who actually plans things out in advance. Dropped plot points, characters that appear and disappear for no apparent reason, aborted plot arcs, pointless meandering without furthering the plot, sub plots that go nowhere, drama for the sake of drama, hints about plot points that are never followed up on, and the big one, shitty endings. There a hell of a lot of pitfalls to pantsing and very few writers are skilled enough to avoid them while writing their stories.

1/2

Anonymous Mon 16 Oct 2023 06:28:48 No.60372478 Report
Quoted By: >>60372541 >>60375576
>>60372429
>>60365343
If you're new then you should have an outline of your story before you even put the first word down. Know who is going to do what, where the plot twists are, what the major plot points are, and how the whole thing is going to end. You don't need a detailed rundown of how every scene is going to play out, in my opinion that's excessive, but at least have a general idea of where to go next when you finish writing each chapter. But don't be afraid to change things as you go along! If you suddenly get the idea that it would be totally cool if X happened in the story instead of Y then go for it! As long as the whole story remains coherent then it's all good.

As the old phrase goes, plans are useless but planning is invaluable.

>Do you just go to the keyboard and pop it out?
After planning it out, yes.

>How do you maintain pace and consistency?
Those are the sorts of things that should be continually monitored as you go along. When you're proofreading try to look for scenes that go on for a little too long, scenes that seem too short, or sections that need to be cut or added entirely. You can still look for potential issues in your outline though, especially when it comes to setting a consistent tone. It might not be a good idea to put a sex scene immediately after a funeral for example.

>How do you know when you need to revise something?
This where judicious levels of proofreading and beta readers come in handy. Ask the thread for help and you're bound to get a few. Try to look for complaints that are happening consistently and fix them since those will likely be problems that the average reader will have as well. On the other hand don't take all of their advice as gospel, if you have a good reason for doing something a certain way then it may be best to go with your original vision.

Hope this helped.

2/2
